    <annotation>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>These be wofull &amp; miserable Strategems in this world.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>Ha[e]c a[e]tas alios mores postulat, aliam vitam desiderat. Hodiernus mundus, totus
                    Chrematisticus, et</marginalia_text>
                </position>
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>acquisititius. Qui in summis</marginalia_text>
                </position>
                <position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
                    <marginalia_text>nauigat, in nummis anchorat.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>Aureum Philippi Macedonis Strategema. Aurum, Regu[m] persuasio. Virtutes ipsa[e], Largitione corrupta[e]
                    , et constuprata[e]. Ca[e]saris Liberalitas, max[im]Ã¨ popularis.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Philip II of Macedon"/>
                    <person name="Julius Caesar"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>This age demands other rules; it desires another life. Today's world is wholly chrematistic and aquiesced. 
                        <!--JG: Unsure about translation of 'acquisititius'--> <!-- CG: So 'chrematisticus' means 'moneyed.' And I think 'acquisitius' is a comparative form meaning something like 'more materialistic.' In other words, an age concerned with money and acquiring things. -->
                He who navigates in the greatest sums,  anchors in money. <!--JG: Tricky to render the 'summis' 'nummis'. Chris, any suggestions?--> <!-- CG: I feel like he's saying 'whoever navigates through the highest circles, anchors himself in coin.' -->
            Gold, the stratagem of Philip II of Macedon. Gold, the persuasion of a king. The virtues themselves corrupted and utterly debauched by bribery. The generosity of Caesar, particularly popular. <!-- CG: Perhaps 'liberality' or 'gift-giving'? This whole passage is a condemnation of using move to buy people. -->
            </translation> 
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>At Vlisses, Heroica Achillis Arma affectauit; eademq[ue] Aiaci pra[e]occupauit: tam precij, quam honoris respectu.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Odysseus"/>
                    <person name="Achilles"/>
                    <person name="Ajax"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>But Odysseus seized the epic arms of Achilles, and worried about the same [arms] of Ajax: 
                both in respect for price and for honour. </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia anchor_text="Aristides" hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>A small commendation for Regulus, Scipio, or Aristides. Almes knightes.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Marcus Atilius Regulus"/>
                    <person name="Scipio Africanus"/>
                    <person name="Aristides"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" text="Aristides" type="straight"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" text="Almes knightes" type="straight"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>Bellisarius, magnus Justiniani Dux, tande[m] Mendicus.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Belisarius"/>
                    <person name="Justinian"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Belisarius, the great general of Justinian, eventually [??].</translation> 
            <!--JG: Chris, what do you make of Mendicus? I assume it's a person, but can't find any information-->
            <!-- CG: Actually I think it's just a description of Belisarius, he eventually becomes a beggar: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Belisarius#Legend_as_a_blind_beggar -->
        </marginalia>
        
